text: hi everyone anthony fantano here
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new quali chris
album ghost at the finish line this guy
is a detroit rapper songwriter producer
he crafted a few of the instrumentals on
danny brown's triple x mixtape and he
has a handful of projects out two of
which have dropped this year this is the
second of them quali chris is an odd
dude however i don't think of him as
being so strange that i would lump him
in with other art rappers such as open
mic eagle or bus driver or milo i don't
really think he's a meme rapper either
or simply absurd and his delivery is far
far far from aggressive however i would
not call it comatose boring or listless
either he's a guy who's just very very
chill however his words are very dense
with word play or deeper meaning or
personal introspections or just straight
up weird jokes he's really an equal
balance of thoughtful playful and
serious there are moments where his
music really reminds me of danny brown
or mf doom or most deaf pusha t or maybe
even like das racist i think there are a
lot of artists out there that have
similar qualities right now to chris and
to me that means potential fans but i
think part of what keeps his music from
translating far outside of the
underground is that he writes his songs
to be so low key chris's songs have
plenty of hooks i wouldn't really say
any of them pop per se and there are
lots of hip-hop artists out there who
evade that sort of song writing and and
they're great doing that they're
completely fine doing that i just think
chris is so eccentric that he has the
potential to make songs that are a bit
catchier a bit more pop savvy because as
of right now like i said a lot of the
courses here very understated like on
the song loop dreams where essentially
we get chris saying and overdubbing
himself saying loop drain loop drain
loop journey
you may get a moment a very dreary
spoken word like on the track king is
dead as the hook or a very eccentric
shouted refrain such as on the track
what up como estab
and another thing that really kind of
kills the flow of some of these tracks
is that structurally chris keeps it so
simple with a lot of these songs
starting with mere fade ins or hardens
and ending with fade outs or just abrupt
finishes the fact that the songs on here
don't start or finish that fantastically
leaves this lp to me feeling like a bit
scatterbrained despite the structuring
and the flow limitations that this lp
has quali chris still manages to
captivate on many songs here there's a
good handful of tracks on here that are
completely whacked out and they feel
bold because of it case in point the
song super this track to me has
chris feeling kind of like a hip-hop
blowfly where he is working out the
calves working on the abs using the
shake weight trying to get in shape for
that
and ever since i heard this album one of
my favorite things to sing in my
apartment has been
super back and then there's the song
coke with denmark and black milk which
instrumentally feels like a beet that
swiss beets would have produced in
bizarro world i love the ridiculous
refrains on the chorus the crazy lyrics
throughout the song and of course the
at the end where we get a club
a club on the flyery ever at the
club it's moments like this where i feel
like chris is at his most surprising at
his most interesting and the closer to
to an extent while i don't like this
song as a finisher i like the
repetitious don't nobody love me don't
nobody let me over a very quirky
spacious synth-heavy beat and i like how
just simple this song is with chris
saying that nobody loves him but things
will change as soon as he gets money the
track does seem a little too dumbed down
to be interesting however in a way it
can kind of be a self-criticism with
chris making so many tracks on this lp
about his time in the rap game and
trying to make it in the rap game and
how maybe he's boiling his passion down
to merely wanting to get money on this
track making it all seem maybe a little
shallow in the long run when chris is
serious on this album he is dead serious
like on the track loop dreams which is
actually a really depressing look at
chris struggling as an independent
artist he's making no traction labels
are too
his fans think he's made it but he
hasn't really made anything and all of
this is performed over a very dreary
beat with a pretty eerie tremolo synthly
that i like a lot and i love the track
undying one of the best instrumentals on
this entire lp with the background
vocals uh
the tom beat that feels really primal on
this thing as well as the jazzy
flourishes of horns that occur
throughout this track too it's just a
really lovely instrumental and this
track is just sort of about chris's
passion for music passion for
success i love the refrain on this track
where he's saying i thought you did it
for the love but i love life and since
it's all connected then i guess i got it
right and then there's the song life
beyond which is sort of an introspective
moment about personal choices and on his
bars here chris reflects upon a lot of
the other artists around him who sort of
influenced him in a positive way in
music black milk danny brown moselle who
actually appears on this track with a
verse and then there's the very eerie
king is dead one of the more chilling
tracks on this lp and there are some
more hard-hitting moments too like the
previously mentioned what up as well as
the song prx with guilty simpson as well
as alchemist with open arms is a bit of
a posse cut i like these tracks i mean
really i like all the tracks there are
only a few that underwhelm me but still
as a whole when i listen to this album i
don't find myself captivated by the
entire thing as an experience because of
just how unorganized and unkempt it is
in a way it's kind of like looking at a
really great sculpture but it feels kind
of unfinished or it feels like the
corners and curves haven't been
completely sanded over or chiseled out
to perfection there's just something
about ghost at the finish line as a
whole that feels kind of uneventful and
while i am drawn to the weirder moments
on this lp maybe there are some tracks
here that i feel aren't such great songs
versus just silly song ideas sort of
like super however it's spots like
this that i think are a testament to
chris's personality because even though
these songs don't feel fleshed out that
heavily don't feel that built up i'm not
getting a great sense of ambition from
the songs on here still chris is such an
eccentric and just off-the-wall rapper
that he shines through a lot of it much
of the time i'm feeling a decent to
strong seven on this
tran position but if you've given this
album a listen what did you think of it
did you love it did you hate it why what
do you think i should review next and
that's it
anthony pantano quali chris
forever
